ce:section.ce:para:
The sensitivity of N, B-CQDs for Cr6+ detection is tested within a wide concentration range of Cr6+ from 0 to 3000 μM. As displayed in Fig. 8
                        a-8c, the PL intensity gradually decreases with the increase of the Cr6+ concentration, implying the high sensitivity of the concentration-dependent fluorescence quenching. It is worth noting that this phenomenon simultaneously occurs under 300, 330, and 490 nm excitation, demonstrating the feasibility of N, B-CQDs as a tri-channel detection of Cr6+. The linear correlation coefficients (R2) at a concentration range of 0–1000 μM are observed as 0.968, 0.994, and 0.954 for the excitation of 300, 330, and 490 nm channels, respectively in Fig. 8d-8f. Furthermore, the higher R2 are obtained as 0.993, 0.992, and 0.996 at a narrow concentration range of 0–100 μM. Accordingly, the LOD can reach as low as 0.054, 0.049, and 0.077 μM, respectively, which are far lower than the maximum level of drinking water (0.962 μM) permitted by the WHO [1]. The lignin-derived N, B-CQDs are comparable to most previously reported CQDs for Cr6+ detection regarding the LOD and linear ranges (Table 1
                        ). These results demonstrate that the high accuracy and reliability of N, B-CQDs-based fluorescent sensors are achieved for the tri-channel detection of Cr6+ in practical application.
